name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: I say personal distaste, because while Trump’s flaws are readily apparent, I don’t believe Piper has made a case that they are uniquely severe in practice - and he does not suggest abstaining for voting for every flawed candidate. Only Trump.

tweet: To be clear, I am questioning the character of John Piper. Is he a good man as far as that goes? I’m sure he is, but he’s still a man, after all. And here he reveals a serious flaw - a disregard for the temporal good of his reader because of a personal distaste for Trump’s flaws.

tweet: Not voting for someone now known to protect the fundamental - including religious - freedoms of your neighbors against an also now known revolutionary left bent on destroying those rights also shows a disregard for the well-being of your countrymen.

tweet: Moreover, how one votes says something about their character, too. Not voting for someone with a now proven record of defending the life of the unborn is different than not voting for someone you aren’t sure will do so. And it reveals a lack of care for your unborn countrymen.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Moreover, some policies reveal character. Trump is a blowhard, but when push comes to shove, he’s shown a resistance to violence and to centralizing control in himself. Those are quite rare virtues - and that they are virtues is undeniable if you are a Christian or conservative.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: We’ve had 45 presidents. Not one was an example of sinlessness. Is Trump’s character uniquely bad? Perhaps, though slave owners, duelers, serial philanderers, and LBJ may have something to say about that.   Here I don’t mean to normalize Trump’s flaws, but to contextualize them.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Piper is also correct that the wages of all sin is death, and that Americanism and Republicanism can be easy idols for believers. But he is wrong to conflate standing for those truths with a stance on voting or not voting for Trump.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Of course, all of this is my humble opinion, and I am only the lowly god-king of @realDailyWire.   Who can say what we’re out there pushing...

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Cool heads, fair investigation, and an understanding that not every horrible thing is THE horrible thing are required to ascertain the truth - which all parties deserve.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: If so, the men deserve punishment. If worse is proven - which again seems unlikely - they deserve more severe punishment. If Arbery was committing a crime, he deserved punishment, too. But not this outcome.   Still, to make of this a major race event seems far-fetched.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: But horrible tragedies can have legal consequences. After a more thorough investigation, it may we’ll be determined that the pursuers did have I’ll-intent or violated Georgia law through recklessness. I strongly suspect the later.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: If, however, Arbery was engaged in a crime - however small - that led to the pursuit - however reckless - then he is not wholly free of responsibility for what, in the end, is likely more horrible tragedy than premeditated murder.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: It’s even possible that Arbery caused the weapon to fire in the struggle.   Does that possibility, or the fact that he charged the weapon at all make him responsible? Probably not. Who wouldn’t charge a weapon pointed at them by some random men chasing them down a street?

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Was he “lynched?” No. He was not executed. He died, as we can all see, struggling over a weapon. Had that struggle not occurred, he may we’ll have been detained until police arrived. But when you act with reckless abandon, as the pursuers seem to have done, people often get hurt.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Is it possible race was a factor? Sure, though likely in more subtle ways than the media would insist. Is it possible race wasn’t a factor? Sure, it’s possible.   That we probably can’t finally determine which is one good argument against so-called hate-crime laws.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: There may well be a time for such a pursuit - I saw a man run out of my house and looked inside to find my wife dead, or something. No claim that rises to that level has been raised here. Whatever Arbery did or didn’t do, it’s hard to imagine how the armed pursuit was merited.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Manslaughter or some other such crime seems more likely. That, by good intention or bad, these men pursued at gunpoint a man who was not in the midst of or immediate aftermath of committing a violent crime and thus created a circumstance that resulted in his untimely demise.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Murder, particularly a racially motivated murder, seems unlikely, though not impossible because the pursuers themselves filmed the affair and didn’t immediately kill Arbery.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: But that such a lose-lose moment came to be in the first place is the result of the fool-hearty at best, malicious at worst actions of the three men who pursued him.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: His death is clearly the result of a struggle over a weapon. Once that struggle begins, both men are engaged in a fight they must have reasonably assumed was for their very lives. Both have a legitimate self-defense claim at that point.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: What’s clear is that Arbery should be alive today. Whether or not he committed a crime at some point or was ‘just jogging’ may provide some context, but are unlikely to change that simple fact.

tweet: @slpng_giants The drumbeat from us is to let people be free to make their own decisions based on their own circumstances.   I'm not saying everyone will come to the same conclusions or that everyone's situation is the same. Of course they aren't.   Beyond that, we don't all agree!

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: @slpng_giants @michaeljknowles @MattWalshBlog @andrewklavan And @benshapiro has come into the office - and shot from his studio - a few times, but has a familial consideration that causes him to be a bit more cautious, though not for his own sake.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: @slpng_giants @michaeljknowles @MattWalshBlog The vast majority of our staff is able to work remotely, but not all.   @andrewklavan has one foot in the grave on a good day. If he can remain at home and still make a living, he should. If he couldn't, that would be a harder assessment.

tweet: @slpng_giants Not all risks are equal. I've come to the office every single day of the lockdown to keep the business running. @michaeljknowles is broadcasting from the studio. @MattWalshBlog lives 3,000 miles away and has always shot in his house - or car.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: @slpng_giants But I won't duck the fact that, yes, I do think people who are at relatively low risk should be afforded the right to go back to work. In the absence of a vaccine or cure, I don't see any way out but through.

tweet: @slpng_giants We're certainly not a non-ideological publication and don't pretend to be. But the conspiracies people form in their minds can be shocking. There are others, but I won't bore you with more of my woe-is-me crap. To borrow from Mamet, "Never feel sorry for a god-king."

tweet: Society is complex - human atoms smashing into other human atoms in our millions and billions. Our concerns are not narrow or theoretical. The man who knows people and has lead people and navigated human relations and endeavors trumps the man of letters in these situations.

tweet: So conservatives aren't technocrats. We want practical leaders, not theoreticians -- EVEN THOUGH the theoretician is likely far smarter and even better informed in his narrow area of expertise, he should not be in charge. He is useful as an advisor, but destructive as a decider.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: This is why, when reality clashes with a model, experts often continue to uphold the model - as in East Anglia or any Stalinist hell-hole. Reality - occupied as it is by the chaos of humanity - just fails to conform to their well-thought-out systems and projections.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Economists love data & systems and, full of the hubris of expertise, fail time-and-again to realize that people are still people. The simple businessman, by contrast, can't afford to be wrong. So, conservatives believe in the invisible hand, not the visible  planner.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: In matters that require understanding human nature in order to predict future outcomes, experts are often hampered by their expertise. PhD economists, for example, rarely understand the economy as well as college drop-out businessmen. Why? Because the economy is people, not data.

tweet: That leads to the next set of questions: Is social distancing even saving hundreds of thousands of lives, or delaying the impact a month or two? Are there less economically destructive ways to save those lives? What costs are we incurring beyond the economic? And others, too.

tweet: The economy often feels abstract, but it isn’t. It’s the livelihoods of billions of people. You can write from home. Airline employees can’t work from home. Not all of the people staying home will have a job to come back to when it’s over. Not every family survives our response.

tweet: So yes, look away. Avoid social and news channels if you can’t deal with the hype. Don’t focus on the 2D flickering zombie if the fear overwhelms. Turn on the lights.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: Some people can have a drink without it owning them; some cannot. Some can eat sweets in moderation; some cannot. It’s the same sin that overwhelms with anxiety that overwhelms with lust or rage or covetousness. And we must treat it the same way.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: If the part of you that wants fear is well-balanced, you can enjoy a horror move now and then or work in dangerous situations. If it’s unbalanced, you should flee from those situations - and any others that cause fear.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: And that’s another aspect. We want fear. We want anxiety. We may not want to want them. We may pray to be freed from them. But if we keep putting our focus on things that make us nervous, it‘s because some part of us wants them.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: It if, at the scariest moment, the theater lights came on and the sound cut off, your focus would return to reality. You wouldn’t feel fear; you’d feel curiosity. What happened?!? You might even feel frustration because you wanted to be afraid.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: But the mechanism given for our protection is so powerful it doesn’t discriminate truth from fantasy. When you watch a horror movie, you aren’t in any danger. You’re in an air-conditioned building surrounded by other normal folk. But you feel fear - sometimes near crippling fear.

name: Jeremy Boreing
tweet: The answer to much of life’s anxiety is actually in this tweet. ‘Everywhere I look...’ Eyes are the lamp of the body. When you put your focus on something scary, it scares you. It’s supposed to! If you saw a bear eating a hiker and DIDN’T feel fear, you’d be dessert!
